========================================================================
ESSENTIA CUSTOM INTEL MKL FFTW STATIC INTEGRATION
========================================================================

This RPM package of Essentia has been built using a custom configuration to 
statically link against Intel oneMKL (Math Kernel Library) for single-precision 
FFT operations, replacing the standard dynamic FFTW3 (fftw3f) dependency.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
1. How the Build Integration Works
------------------------------------------------------------------------
Because Essentia's Waf build tool does not have a direct "--with-mkl" configuration 
flag, we redirect standard FFTW3 lookups using pkg-config.

During the RPM build process:
- The build script dynamically searches /opt/intel/ for oneMKL pkg-config files 
  (specifically "mkl-static-lp64-seq.pc") and exposes them to the build path.
- A dummy "fftw3f.pc" file is dynamically generated in the build root.
- This dummy file maps the libs and cflags variables to point to the static 
  oneMKL libraries (libmkl_intel_lp64.a, libmkl_sequential.a, and libmkl_core.a).
- The build environment prepends the dummy pc file location to PKG_CONFIG_PATH.
- When Essentia's configuration scripts check for "fftw3f", they load our dummy 
  file and link libessentia statically against the Intel MKL libraries.

------------------------------------------------------------------------
2. Runtime Usage & Shared Library Resolution
------------------------------------------------------------------------
The resulting shared library "libessentia.so" is completely self-contained with 
respect to MKL. Only the specific FFT/DFT routines utilized by Essentia are 
extracted from the static MKL archives during linking.

As a result:
- There are ZERO external dynamic library dependencies on "libmkl_*.so.2" at runtime.
- The package requires no runtime configuration of LD_LIBRARY_PATH, setvars.sh, 
  or system-wide /etc/ld.so.conf.d/ paths.
- The footprint remains extremely small (~1.9MB RPM payload size) due to compiler 
  dead-code elimination of unused MKL symbols.
========================================================================
